they're bloody stupid.

BUFFY THE VAMPIRE SLAYER
Season Five, Episode 16: &quot;The Body&quot;
Writers: Joss Whedon
Director: Joss Whedon

&quot;The Body&quot; is obviously the defining episode of this period of the
show.  And it's a pretty good episode for me.  I don't think it's
among the show's best.  A lot of that is centered around the early
parts, which simply don't do their professed job of evoking the
physical side of the reaction to death - I find that all the
directorial flourishes distance me rather than being immersive.  There
are some intense moments (Buffy meeting Dawn at school is incredibly
raw, and for some reason I didn't appreciate it last time), and I keep
focusing on the roles of Anya and Tara, whose reactions to death are
quite interesting in addition to being so well performed.  I think I
feel maybe 70% of what Joss was trying for.  Obviously, it had 100% of
its intended effect on many people, so, uh, more power to everyone in
that category.
Rating: Good

Season Five, Episode 17: &quot;Forever&quot;
Writer: Marti Noxon
Director: Marti Noxon

&quot;Forever&quot; is one of those episodes I really want to like.  It's right
to take another episode specifically as a wind-down from the previous
one before going back to our silly* fantasy hellgod plot.  I've talked
before about how well it captures the oppressiveness of the mundane as
the people who've been by Buffy's side through dangerous times now try
to be her support and to take charge of grappling with things like how
to word a funeral program.  &quot;Forever&quot; does a good job shifting from
there from Buffy's headspace to Dawn's, and I very much approve of the
decision of what to show and not to show about the resurrection
ritual.  The very end is fascinating for both sisters' reactions.  On
top of that, Doc makes an immediate impression in his debut, and I
*love* Angel's visit, which plays on both what he and Buffy can and
can't do for each other in their neediest times.  It's a special one-
time guest spot that doesn't need to be anything more.  But &quot;Forever&quot;
is also not without its heaping share of flaws, and there's a worn-out
quality to staging, dialogue, and performance, like there just wasn't
enough energy left to make it more than a &quot;minor&quot; episode.  The first
signs of organ failure show up in the unnatural Willow/Tara dialogue
and the lazy composition of the egg-stealing sequence.  And then right
before that nice ending, during the Buffy/Dawn confrontation prior to
the knock at the door... Well, the episode absolutely dies, leaving the
actors buried under leaden dialogue that talks about high emotions
that they're not able to bring.  There's enough good in this show to
wish that it could've been a stronger contender.
Rating: Decent

Season Five, Episode 18: &quot;Intervention&quot;
Writer: Jane Espenson
Director: Michael Gershman

Another popular one for some, this is like an experiment to see how
well BTVS would work without some of its internal sense of logic.  The
dialogue in some part crackles, particularly in the episode's best
plot thread, as Buffy summons up some quips while she goes on a Hokey
Pokey inspired quest and receives a nicely ambiguous and intriguing
message.  The rest of the episode seems designed to be a sort of a
follow-up to &quot;Crush&quot; in which both Buffy and Spike are made to
understand, in a way they hadn't before, the level of nobility he's
capable of when driven by this obsession.  Meanwhile, in order to get
to that point, the robot humor starts to wear thin after awhile, the
Scoobies seem remarkably slow to catch on to their best friend being
replaced by a machine, and the Ben half of Glory lets the Glory half
in on a few secrets by being a moron.  As for that last scene, since
the original review I've made my peace with everything about it except
for that damn kiss.  Without the kiss, it'd be a strong piece of
drama, but with it, I don't buy it in the slightest.
Rating: Decent

Season Five, Episode 19: &quot;Tough Love&quot;
Writer: Rebecca Rand Kirshner
Director: David Grossman

And here's an experiment to see if BTVS can stand without its ear for
dialogue.  Surprisingly well, actually, at least over the short term.
At this point there's enough good will so that I have a built-in
interest in these people and their lives even when the individual
conversations aren't so special.  Some are trying to convey worthwhile
themes (Buffy/Giles), and some cover worthwhile topics in an awkwardly
contrived-looking way (the Willow/Tara argument), but I'm seeing the
worthwhile-ness.  Of course, those who appreciate TL will surely agree
that it's at its best when the dialogue drops out, with sequences like
the mopey pan through the cheerful looking fair, or the brutality of
the whole well-timed sequence in which Tara unexpectedly finds Glory
next to her, and gets her hand crushed before losing her mind while
Willow looks on.

One thing that elicited some disagreement last time is the part in
which Wil tries to take on the hell-god solo.  The amount of magic
involved gets mixed opinions; some love seeing Willow tap into
something this cosmic while others miss her being normal, and mystical
stuff as a whole being more special rather than commonplace.  I'm in
the former category largely because of Willow - I'm impressed by the
process of seeing this cute mousy (don't usually lose that adjective)
girl turn into this witch bursting with this righteous rage, avenging
her fallen lover.  One of the joys of serialized TV is when a
character undergoes a transformation like this over the course of
years.  In that moment I believe, just for a split second, that she
might actually be able to win, and I'm a little worried about where
this uncontrollable energy might lead.  It's a very strong bit, for
people in my camp, although I understand the dissenting opinion.  The
part I don't understand is why some people find the floating and
visual effects to be cheesy - by any objective standard, it looks
fucking great.  Anyway, the end of the season drags substantially for
me, but &quot;Tough Love,&quot; by itself, is a reasonably taut little big-
episode.
Rating: Good (up from Decent)

Additional comments on S5D5:  I think most people who'd be reading
this already know this, but apparently in the original outline for the
season, which got changed very early in the year, &quot;Tough Love&quot; was
basically supposed to be the part of Willow's arc that eventually made
it into &quot;Seeing Red&quot; and &quot;Villains.&quot;  Like Joss, I prefer the timing
that they ended up with, really taking the time to let her and Tara be
together.

James Marsters does not appear in TB.  The last time a BTVS was absent
in an episode for which he was credited was David Boreanaz, also
playing a vampire, in &quot;Inca Mummy Girl,&quot; another episode involving a
corpse... Yeah, in case you haven't noticed, I have nothing else of note
to say.

*Don't take the use of that adjective too seriously, okay?  I'm
applying &quot;silly&quot; to the &quot;plot&quot; rather than the &quot;story,&quot; if that makes
sense.

Thoughts?

-AOQ
