Buffy makes a little connection with them too in the hospital.  Well, she
does with everyone actually - even as she stays in her weird head space.
But Xander, Willow &amp; Giles are pretty much to be expected.  Long time
closeness with them.  Tara is a little new in this special sense.  When she
speaks of her own experience with loss, I think it was the moment that most
helped Buffy.

Anya is another matter.  Her oft referenced monologue back in Willow's room
is good stuff, but I think I prefer her brief remarks at the hospital.

Anya: (a little too loudly) I wish that Joyce didn't die...
Anya: (more quietly) ...because she was nice. And now we all hurt.

It's pure Anya in delivery and content.  Yet, for all its awkwardness, it
communicates perfectly and poignantly.  Anya does seem to have a knack for
sensing the mood of the room.  And it speaks well for her development as
human.  Xander has taught her well.

The Body as an episode tends not to speak too directly to the season and
series.  (Beyond the fact and implications of Joyce's death that one could
probably figure out by simply saying she died.)  But it does brush against
it here and there.  One is the waiting room scene in general - a scene
that's just filled with love.  As sad as it is, everybody's heart is
together in support of Buffy on a level we rarely see.  Two episodes from
now, Buffy's spirit guide is going to tell her that she's filled with love.
I tend to think of love as sort of the stealth theme of the season -
directly introduced late in a season so geared towards death.  But love is
kind of the foundation of family and comes to be shown at the end as giving
death meaning.  The latter experienced a different way in this episode.

Anyway, back to Tara and Anya.  This is a really good example of Tara as a
kind of gentle personal counselor I guess.  (Not sure how else to describe
it.)  Which shows up once in a while as one of her better traits - something
I always associate with the character.  A kind of unassuming wisdom.  It's
sad, though I suppose inevitable, that it eventually comes to chafe a little
on Willow.  Familiarity breeds contempt is probably too harsh a description
of the process, but it's a cousin to it I think.

Buffy seems to genuinely appreciate Anya's sentiments - which I think I'll
leave at that.  Some day I want to think more about how/if/when Buffy and
Anya connect in this series.  I've never been happy with the way that was
handled the second half of S7.

