&gt; to word a funeral program.
">

The downside of The Body is that it doesn't deal with the aftermath.  So
you've get two shows dealing directly with Joyce's death instead of one.
All that bleakness nearly buries this episode.  The oppressiveness of the
mundane you refer to goes on for quite a while.  And sometimes it's pretty
good (though I'm not wild about the coffin buying scene), but it's always
bleak.  I feel exhausted by the episode before it really gets going.

When talk turns to resurrection (and sex as affirmation of life) it starts
picking up.  The episode does a nice job, I think, of sliding Glory into the
mix, thereby achieving the major function of linking back up with the
seasonal story.  (I like how Jinx is running out of superlatives to utter
about Glory.)  It also advances the Willow/Tara story, reconnects Spike and
Dawn, introduces a small but important character, and ends up hitting
squarely on the theme of Buffy carrying the weight of the world now that
Joyce is dead.

It's not really a big episode, but it puts some valuable things out there.
With that in mind, the episode on the whole improves as it moves along for
me rather than the reverse you find.  Even if some individual moments aren't
the best.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; &quot;Forever&quot; does a good job shifting from
&gt; there from Buffy's headspace to Dawn's, and I very much approve of the
&gt; decision of what to show and not to show about the resurrection
&gt; ritual.  The very end is fascinating for both sisters' reactions.
