I'm not sure what to make of Dawn tearing up the photo.  The aspect of
Buffy's part that gets me is that, even as she's breaking down over the
impossibility of it, she is utterly uncompromising as to the task she
assigns to herself.  She's decided she has to be mom.  Not big sister
working with little sister, all with more responsibilities.  Nope.  She has
to be mom.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; On
&gt; top of that, Doc makes an immediate impression in his debut, and I
&gt; *love* Angel's visit, which plays on both what he and Buffy can and
&gt; can't do for each other in their neediest times.
">

Angel says Buffy will get help from her friends.  But it starts getting hard
to see that.  Buffy effectively pleads with Angel for help.  Stay forever.
Angel doesn't exactly say no - they both just know it can't be.  Even as
they dream for a sec that it might be possible.  But however it was done,
the answer still was no.  A few episodes from now, Giles will say no to a
similar, more serious request.  And when Buffy ask who's going to be mom at
the end of this episode, the implication is that it can only be Buffy.

I think this Angel visit has to be the most out of context cross-over of the
two series.  Others don't really connect the series, but they aren't in
opposition to it either.  This time, however, it's nigh on impossible to
imagine the Angel of AtS at this point in time acting like this at all.
&quot;Let me worry about the neediness. I can handle it.&quot;  Yeah, right.  Not that
there has to be a connection.  Just making an observation.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; It's a special one-
&gt; time guest spot that doesn't need to be anything more.  But &quot;Forever&quot;
&gt; is also not without its heaping share of flaws, and there's a worn-out
