&gt; enough energy left to make it more than a &quot;minor&quot; episode.  The first
&gt; signs of organ failure show up in the unnatural Willow/Tara dialogue
">

I like the one with Dawn.  The one where they discover the book missing is
clunky.

The sentiments, however, work very well for me, and are, I believe,
foundational for much of what will happen between Willow and Tara for a long
time.

On the very short term, we see an excellent example of Tara being more
knowledgeable than Willow.  This plays well into what we find has been a
growing sense of discomfort with that by Willow.  I think that's mostly
surface though.  I believe something deeper is shown with the evident
different attitude towards resurrection spells that the two have.  Willow
seems to genuinely have no idea what might be wrong with them other than
technical failure, while Tara has a whole ethical belief system built around
it.  We're seeing a pretty substantial gulf between them in moral outlook.
That may not be the direct subject of their upcoming fight (though S6
implications seem clear), but that kind of fundamental difference not fully
recognized would likely be a background irritant trying to work its way out.
I think Tara's remark about being frightened by Willow's power (in Tough
Love) touches upon that gulf.

The resurrection spell also lays the groundwork for Buffy's S6 resurrection.
It shows Willow's willingness to go there.  (It's interesting that Tara
agrees to go along with Willow then.)  It introduces the ethical conundrum
generally speaking, and displays some of Spike's attitude towards the
subject.  And it introduces the concept of coming back wrong.

All in all making this aspect of the episode rather momentous and
fascinating.

