I say instinctive rather than calculated because it seems to have come to
her as a complete thought rather than constructed through logic - even
though there is a logic behind it.  In my imagination a dozen possible
reactions flashed through her head, and that's the one that felt right.
Rationalizing it would take a bit longer.  (Maybe even change her mind.)
But it's not quite impulse, which implies a degree of casualness and trivial
motive.  There's a gravitas to it that properly speaks to her gratitude, his
sacrifice and recognition of what matters to each of them.

Or another way of looking at it is as a different example of Buffy's knack
for seeing a situation and knowing what to do.  Wisdom is something else
that can work like that.  At least if you view &quot;wisdom&quot; as different than
intelligence, and not necessarily logic based.  Though again, it can be
logically explained in retrospect.

I don't believe that it much matters that Buffy doesn't make a habit of
offering such kisses.  I think the scene pretty clearly presents it as
something singular.  That it's not normal is part of its power.  And the
choice of kiss is defined by what would be valuable to Spike, not by Buffy's
own standards.  (Vague Disclaimer would describe it as throwing Spike a
bone.)

But maybe she thought it out more than I give Buffy credit for.  We are,
after all, stuck analyzing the limited information offered in a TV scene.
It could be whatever anybody's imagination wants it to be.  In mixing the
perspectives I think I'm also saying that I believe it works both
emotionally and logically.

