The short answer I think is both.  Anya is the sum of her life.  The
somewhat longer answer is that Anya's personality/manner was developed
during her first bout as human.  Her lack of understanding of
humanity/society and so on is from lack of meaningful contact, both as human
and demon, though 1100 years as a demon is rather longer than 17 as a human.
In other words, what little social skills she had originally were probably
forgotten after 1100 years of disuse, but she appears to have had minimal
social interaction to begin with.  Her extensive knowledge of demon lore and
her use of demon life as a standard by which to measure human life comes
from her demon experience.  More recently has been the Xander influence
which has disrupted, but not overcome her prior influences.

The really long answer requires an analysis of Anya's lack of self identity
and how that fuels her isolation, her fear of rejection, her greed, her
uncritical acceptance of assorted outside influences (as in latching onto
both capitalism and communism at different times, becoming all about
vengeance, and living her life through Xander), her tendency to abstract
feelings (perversely paired with poorly controlled outbursts of feeling),
and probably just about everything else in her nature.  But I don't care to
go fully into that now.  Hopefully that adequately hints at the direction.

Any way I look at it, though, it's not an either or proposition.

OBS
