tones.  That's also part of my problem with &quot;Earshot,&quot; actually; if I
can be permitted a moment of pretension, Jane and I have different
ideas about writing, extending beyond this series to BSG.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; I don't love it, but it could have been worse -- they could have made it a
&gt; *romantic* kiss.  Instead, Buffy's attitude after the kiss shows that it
&gt; was a one-time reward, not something that should get his hopes up;  and
&gt; the whole episode shows us over and over again how *wrong* a Buffy-Spike
&gt; love would be, so we need not fear that the writers are going down that
&gt; path without justification.  Given that, it's ... tolerable, I'll say.
&gt; (Note: I'm not saying anything now about whether or not a rather different
&gt; Spuffy love works in S7.)
">

I'd known basically from the beginning that Buffy and Spike would get
together, and that a certain segment of the fanbase tended to get
annoyingly squeely about it.  So I was basically prepared to hate it
whenever it happened.  Maybe that didn't give me false hope that they
wouldn't hook up, but it also made me appreciate perhaps even more
than an unspoiled viewer how many times the show had the chance to go
down that path without justification, and didn't.  For years, BTVS
doesn't pull the trigger until it makes sense to do so, and when they
finally do find something resembling love towards the very end of the
series, the show has earned it.

On the other hand, Glory's &quot;This isn't over!&quot; annoyed me

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; more this time.  When I become a recurring villain, I'm going to have
&gt; security cameras in my air ducts, and I'm never going to shout &quot;This isn't
&gt; over!&quot;  But at least they paid it off in the final scene, instead of just
&gt; leaving it as an empty cliche.
">

I'll remember you said that.  Expect us to hold you to it.

I really wasn't expecting the final scene the first time, but in
retrospect, of course it had to go that way.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
